00:16:53,770 --> 00:17:00,330
You have your own room. I have another. Both doors stay closed. Go on. In public, you're my wife.

185
00:17:00,650 --> 00:17:06,630
You go to events with me. You smile when it's time to smile. You don't need to pretend more than that.

186
00:17:06,830 --> 00:17:13,010
In private, nothing. I won't touch you. I won't go into your room. I won't ask about your life.

187
00:17:13,390 --> 00:17:18,950
And you won't ask about mine. No questions. No questions. I set the cup on the saucer.

188
00:17:18,950 --> 00:17:24,250
I thought that no questions had the smell of a locked door. And locked doors were exactly the

189
00:17:24,250 --> 00:17:30,330
ones I always wanted to open. For how long? One year. After that, you can ask for the separation

190
00:17:30,330 --> 00:17:36,110
without any contest from me. If you'd rather stay longer, it's negotiable. Why me? It was the first

191
00:17:36,110 --> 00:17:41,370
question of mine that took him a second longer to answer. Just a second. Because you need it.

192
00:17:41,570 --> 00:17:46,430
His voice dropped half a tone. And because I need a wife for reasons that don't fit into this

193
00:17:46,430 --> 00:17:52,230
conversation, I held his gaze. He held mine. Neither of us blinked for a stretch of time that

194
00:17:52,230 --> 00:17:57,750
would have been awkward at any other table. I'll think about it. I said, you haven't till tomorrow morning.

195
00:17:58,590 --> 00:18:03,290
Me. He took from the inner pocket of his jacket, a cream-colored card with tall, firm handwriting.

196
00:18:03,790 --> 00:18:10,270
The address of a city hall. If you show up, it's yes. If you don't, it's no. I took the card.

197
00:18:10,750 --> 00:18:15,070
Our fingers didn't touch, but they passed so close that I felt the warmth of his hand for

198
00:18:15,070 --> 00:18:21,790
a second before I pulled mine back. Do you always negotiate like this? I asked two sentences in a card?

199
00:18:22,270 --> 00:18:27,690
No. He leaned back in his chair. But with you, I didn't want to make things up. I stood up from

200
00:18:27,690 --> 00:18:33,310
the table. I didn't thank him for the coffee. He didn't expect me to. I walked to the door with my

201
00:18:33,310 --> 00:18:38,620
backstrate, knowing all of Providence would be recounting this scene for weeks. When I touched the

202
00:18:38,620 --> 00:18:45,760
handle, I heard behind me, low. Almost thought aloud. Two sugar cubes, a drop of milk.

203
00:18:46,320 --> 00:18:52,400
I stopped. I looked over my shoulder. What? Ludovico didn't look at me. He was stirring his own coffee

204
00:18:52,400 --> 00:18:58,160
with a small spoon. That's how you take it. When you're not testing me, I stood there a second longer

205
00:18:58,160 --> 00:19:05,500
than I should have. Then I opened the door and left. I slept badly. I woke before the sun.

206
00:19:05,500 --> 00:19:11,240
I shoured. Put on the least wrinkled blue dress in my closet. Gathered my documents into a small

207
00:19:11,240 --> 00:19:16,400
bag and went down the stairs without saying goodbye to a single thing. I left a short note

208
00:19:16,400 --> 00:19:21,780
for Narina on the kitchen table. The kind that explains nothing and promises everything. I'd have to

209
00:19:21,780 --> 00:19:27,280
take the scolding later. City Hall was three blocks from the harbor. I arrived 15 minutes before

210
00:19:27,280 --> 00:19:32,980
nine. He was already there. Leaning against the corridor wall. Hands in his jacket pockets.

211
00:19:32,980 --> 00:19:37,580
Looking at his own shoe like someone who'd been waiting long enough to have memorized the floor.

212
00:19:38,080 --> 00:19:43,240
Beside him, an older man, broad shouldered, but the look of someone who'd come back from

213
00:19:43,240 --> 00:19:49,440
wars no one had named. Ludovico raised his head when he saw me. He didn't smile. He made no ceremony.

214
00:19:50,120 --> 00:19:56,260
He just waited for me to arrive. Good morning. I said, good morning. He made a discrete gesture

215
00:19:56,260 --> 00:20:02,300
toward the man beside him. Bastion del Rose. He works with me. He'll be nearby whenever you go out.

216
00:20:02,300 --> 00:20:09,100
Bastion tilted his head half a degree. No hello, no pleasure, no smile, just the half degree.

217
00:20:09,660 --> 00:20:15,120
Nice to meet you. I answered anyway because my grandmother would have smacked me if I didn't answer.

218
00:20:15,660 --> 00:20:19,280
The clerk called us. We went into a small room with a long table.

219
00:20:19,800 --> 00:20:24,580
Papers already prepared. Ludovico pushed them toward me before the clerk could open his mouth.

220
00:20:25,020 --> 00:20:30,960
Read it. Slowly. If there's any claws you don't accept, we redo it. I read every line.

221
00:20:30,960 --> 00:20:34,820
It was exactly the way he'd said in the cafe. Separate rooms,

222
00:20:35,500 --> 00:20:42,040
appearances in public, no questions, one year, right of unilateral exit on her part. I

223
00:20:42,040 --> 00:20:46,960
reached the last page and slid my finger down to the signature line. I saw nothing I wasn't supposed

224
00:20:46,960 --> 00:20:54,360
to see. Not then. It's fine. I said, I signed. He signed after me. The clerk stamped it.

225
00:20:54,600 --> 00:21:00,580
There was no kiss, no photo, no rice thrown on the way out. The three of us left city hall in

226
00:21:01,180 --> 00:21:08,020
the car was waiting. Black, glossy, glass-to-dark. The kind my father used to tell me not to

227
00:21:08,020 --> 00:21:13,700
look at when I was a child. Bestion opened the rear door. Ludovico got in from the other side and sat

228
00:21:13,700 --> 00:21:17,780
next to me without saying anything. The car took the road toward the upper suburb.

229
00:21:18,320 --> 00:21:23,580
Providence shrank in the window. The red rooftops falling away behind us. In green took over.

230
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:29,120
He didn't speak the entire way. Neither did I. The mansion gate appeared after 20 minutes.

231
00:21:29,120 --> 00:21:35,720
Dark iron, tall, with a discreet crest in the center. A lion's head with the crown split in two.

232
00:21:36,020 --> 00:21:41,620
I didn't ask what it meant. It was part of the no questions. The gate opened. The car went up a

233
00:21:41,620 --> 00:21:47,080
lane of low trees. I saw the house before I knew it was a house. Three stories of pale stone,

234
00:21:47,480 --> 00:21:53,140
tall windows, a double staircase at the entrance. A small woman, my grandmother's age,

235
00:21:53,140 --> 00:21:58,740
appeared at the door above. Her pulled into a low bun, white apron, dry hands,

236
00:21:59,440 --> 00:22:05,480
donachyata, Ludovico said, this is Yolanda. Donachyata looked me over from head to toe,

237
00:22:05,860 --> 00:22:10,860
not with judgment, with concern. The kind of look only a kitchen woman knows how to give.

238
00:22:11,300 --> 00:22:17,780
Welcome. She said, you must be tired. I'm fine. She didn't believe me, but she nodded and didn't

239
00:22:17,780 --> 00:22:23,120
insist. Ludovico took me upstairs. The upper corridor was long, with identical door

240
00:22:23,120 --> 00:22:28,220
as on both sides. He stopped at the third door on the right and opened it. This is your room.

241
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:34,780
It was too big for one person. A canopy double bed, a desk at the window, a built-in closet

242
00:22:34,780 --> 00:22:41,300
along an entire wall. Everything in shades of cream and gray, a tasteful cold. My room is at the end

243
00:22:41,300 --> 00:22:46,960
of the corridor. He said, behind me, on the left side, you don't need to go past it. Understood?

244
00:22:46,960 --> 00:22:54,600
If you need anything, Donachyata is always nearby. And you, he paused a second. If you need me,

245
00:22:54,920 --> 00:22:59,220
Donachyata knows where I am. I turned to look at him. He was standing in the doorway,

246
00:22:59,740 --> 00:23:04,680
one hand on the handle, looking at some point between my shoulder and the window. For the first time

247
00:23:04,680 --> 00:23:11,060
since the cafe, he seemed unsure of where to put his gaze. Thank you. I said, I wasn't quite sure

248
00:23:11,060 --> 00:23:16,580
why. He tilted his head a fraction of a millimeter. Close the door. I heard his footsteps go

249
00:23:16,580 --> 00:23:22,000
down the corridor, in silence. I sat on the edge of the bed. I ran my hand over the dovet,

250
00:23:22,380 --> 00:23:26,840
and the fabric was soft in a way that made my eyes sting without warning. I didn't cry.

251
00:23:27,360 --> 00:23:32,400
Not that first afternoon. That night, Donachyata came up with a tray, hot soup,

252
00:23:32,720 --> 00:23:38,320
fresh bread, a glass of red wine. I didn't ask her to swap it for water. I drank the wine to the

253
00:23:38,320 --> 00:23:42,700
last drop. I lay down without changing my clothes and stared at the ceiling of the canopy.

254
00:23:42,700 --> 00:23:49,360
Near midnight, I heard footsteps in the corridor, slow, measured footsteps. They came from the

255
00:23:49,360 --> 00:23:54,520
end of the corridor. They reached my door. They stopped. They stood there for a stretch of time. I

256
00:23:54,520 --> 00:24:01,780
couldn't measure. Five seconds. Ten. More than ten. He didn't knock. He didn't call out. He made no

257
00:24:01,780 --> 00:24:07,820
sound. Then the footsteps went back. I heard them move away slowly. The same rhythm in the direction

258
00:24:07,820 --> 00:24:13,700
they had come from. The door at the end of the corridor opened. Closed. I stared at the canopy in the

259
00:24:13,700 --> 00:24:19,680
same position and understood, lying in that bed too big for one person, that the man the town feared

260
00:24:19,680 --> 00:24:25,700
had come to my door on the first night. Not to come in, not to speak. Only to stop outside,

261
00:24:26,160 --> 00:24:32,920
and then go back. I closed my eyes. I didn't sleep. The Karatio Lomanshin woke before I did. I

262
00:24:32,920 --> 00:24:36,900
discovered this on the first morning when I came down the marble stairs still in my robe

263
00:24:36,900 --> 00:24:42,940
fastened up to my neck and found the house already breathing. Donachiyara, tidying the sideboard in the

264
00:24:42,940 --> 00:24:47,960
hall, the smell of fresh bread coming from the kitchen. A staff member I didn't recognize cleaning

265
00:24:47,960 --> 00:24:53,060
the vestibule stained glass with silent movements. No one looked at me as if I didn't belong there.

266
00:24:53,440 --> 00:24:58,220
No one looked at me as if I belonged either. It was worse than hostility. It was professional

267
00:24:58,220 --> 00:25:04,080
neutrality. Good morning, ma'am. Donachiyara said, seeing me standing in the kitchen archway.

268
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:10,060
Coffee here or in the garden room, it took me a second to understand that ma'am was me. Here is fine,

269
00:25:10,460 --> 00:25:16,580
I answered. If it's not in the way, she laughed softly. The kind of laugh only Italian women of a certain

270
00:25:16,580 --> 00:25:21,480
age know how to give without taking their hands off their apron. You, in the way in my kitchen,

271
00:25:22,080 --> 00:25:27,280
that's a good one. I sat on the wooden bench against the counter. Donachiyara said a cup in front of

272
00:25:27,280 --> 00:25:32,220
me without asking how I wanted it. Two sugar cubes had been dissolved in it. A drop of milk

273
00:25:32,220 --> 00:25:37,200
had been added on top. The coffee was exactly the color I'd been drinking since I was 15.

274
00:25:37,780 --> 00:25:43,320
I held the cup with both hands. Did you tell Mr. Ludovico? Donachiyara kept stirring a pot on the

275
00:25:43,320 --> 00:25:49,220
stove without turning around. No one needed to tell me anything, my dear. Mr. Ludovico left it noted.

276
00:25:49,520 --> 00:25:55,420
He asked that it be this way every day. She paused briefly. Always. I drank the coffee too slowly.

277
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:01,440
That was how the first week went. I'd discover a house rule by accident. And Ludovico had already

278
00:26:01,440 --> 00:26:07,060
altered the rule in silence so I'd fit inside it. On Monday, I mentioned aloud to Donachiyara

279
00:26:07,060 --> 00:26:12,240
that I missed the bookside left in my apartment. On Tuesday, three of my favorites were on the

280
00:26:12,240 --> 00:26:18,340
little table in my room with new bookmarks between the pages. On Wednesday, I told Bastion I hated

281
00:26:18,340 --> 00:26:23,580
the black car because it reminded me of a funeral. I only said it sarcastically, because he

282
00:26:23,580 --> 00:26:28,800
appeared in a dark suit in the corridor and I wanted to provoke him. On Thursday, Bastion appeared

283
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:33,400
at the winter garden door with his hands folded in front of his body, with the stone face that

284
00:26:33,400 --> 00:26:38,360
was already his trademark. He asked me to ask whether you'd prefer the gray car or the black one to

285
00:26:38,360 --> 00:26:45,140
go out today. I looked up from my book. Do I have something scheduled today? You will, if you want to.

286
00:26:45,460 --> 00:26:51,760
He blinked once. Bastion, I said, trying not to laugh. Were you always like this or were you trained?

287
00:26:52,320 --> 00:26:57,280
Both, ma'am. And he went back down the corridor with a step identical to the one he derived with.

288
00:26:57,280 --> 00:27:01,400
I kept staring at the door for half a minute with the book forgotten in my lap,

289
00:27:01,880 --> 00:27:06,260
and admitted to myself that this house was starting to become an intimate joke I had an asked to be

290
00:27:06,260 --> 00:27:11,860
part of. The problem was, the joke had an owner, and the owner of the joke didn't smile.

291
00:27:12,620 --> 00:27:17,560
Ludovico and I crossed paths with icy formality. In the corridor, he'd nod,

292
00:27:18,200 --> 00:27:24,240
half a degree, enough not to be rude. At dinner, we sat at the two ends of the long table like two

293
00:27:24,240 --> 00:27:29,280
chest pieces pretending the board was too big for any attack. He'd ask if I'd needed anything.

294
00:27:29,860 --> 00:27:35,680
I'd answer no. He'd ask if Dona Chiarra had been kind. I'd answer that she was an angel. He'd

295
00:27:35,680 --> 00:27:41,620
fold his napkin and stand up. No questions. That was the rule. He kept the rule better than I did.

296
00:27:42,120 --> 00:27:46,220
Wednesday evening, Narina showed up at the gate with a leather bag that looked like it weighed

297
00:27:46,220 --> 00:27:51,800
more than she did. Bastion opened the gate for her without arguing. Dona Chiarra hugged her like

298
00:27:52,700 --> 00:27:57,680
Narina walked through the hall with wide eyes and a comment on the tip of her tongue. This place

299
00:27:57,680 --> 00:28:02,680
looks like a museum with tasteful ghosts. I pulled her into the kitchen before Ludovico could

300
00:28:02,680 --> 00:28:09,500
appear. Sweetie, she whispered, taking a Tupperware container out of her bag. I brought my grandmother's

301
00:28:09,500 --> 00:28:14,960
lasagna, not that Dona Chiarra needs help, but my grandma liked you, and I wasn't going to let

302
00:28:14,960 --> 00:28:21,780
that slide. You're a social hazard. I know. Where does he sleep? Narina? Just so I know the distance

303
00:28:21,780 --> 00:28:28,000
between the two rooms, Missy. It's field research. We sat on the kitchen bench, split the lasagna

304
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:32,580
into two bowls, and ate in secret like two teenagers who'd snuck out of the cafeteria.

305
00:28:38,210 --> 00:28:43,430
It was the first time I'd laughed since the church bell. I laughed for real. My face half lowered,

306
00:28:44,130 --> 00:28:50,130
almost choking on a piece of cheese. Dona Chiarra passed by the door, pretended not to see,

307
00:28:50,390 --> 00:28:54,950
and kept going toward the garden. Ludovico passed by the door five minutes later.

308
00:28:54,950 --> 00:29:00,830
He also pretended not to see, but I saw him. He had his shirts leave rolled up to the elbow,

309
00:29:01,250 --> 00:29:06,450
his hair a little out of place. The kind of detail I shouldn't have registered. He stopped in the

310
00:29:06,450 --> 00:29:12,290
archway for half a second. Exactly long enough to identify me laughing, and kept going down the corridor

311
00:29:12,290 --> 00:29:17,650
without saying anything. Narina gave me a discreet kick on the foot under the bench. Sweetie,

312
00:29:18,030 --> 00:29:23,010
she whispered, mouthful. That man just looked at you the way you look at an open window in the middle

313
00:29:23,010 --> 00:29:28,470
of winter. Shut up. It's a professional observation. You're a music teacher, Narina.

314
00:29:29,170 --> 00:29:35,050
Music is observation, my girl. What do you think we listen to? I nudged her with my elbow. She laughed.

315
00:29:35,590 --> 00:29:39,870
Dona Chiarra came back with a picture of water as if nothing had happened. I took a long

316
00:29:39,870 --> 00:29:46,210
sip and said nothing more. That night, when Narina left, the corridor was too silent. I passed the

317
00:29:46,210 --> 00:29:51,830
library door, and saw the light on under the crack. I didn't go in. I went to my room,

318
00:29:51,830 --> 00:29:57,630
closed the door, and took a long time to fall asleep. The kitchen was too big for crying at dawn.

319
00:29:58,050 --> 00:30:03,590
I discovered this three days later, on Monday, when I came down barefoot at three in the morning,

320
00:30:04,110 --> 00:30:09,170
because I'd woken with my heart in my throat, and a dream of an empty church stuck to my neck.

321
00:30:09,590 --> 00:30:15,030
I turned on only the light above the stove. I sat on the cold floor with my back against the cabinet.

322
00:30:15,450 --> 00:30:20,410
The crying came without sound. The way I'd learned to cry when I lived with my grandmother,

323
00:30:20,410 --> 00:30:26,250
and she didn't like to hear sadness after ten at night. I heard the footsteps before I saw his

324
00:30:26,250 --> 00:30:31,450
shadow in the archway. He didn't turn on the main light. He stood there for two seconds in the doorway,

325
00:30:32,050 --> 00:30:37,630
in a white shirt open at the collar. His hair sang he hadn't slept either. He didn't ask anything.

326
00:30:37,950 --> 00:30:43,150
I lifted my chin before he could think of touching me. I don't need an audience to cry. Thank you.

327
00:30:43,390 --> 00:30:47,990
He stopped in a very specific way, without retreating or advancing. He just stayed.

328
00:30:47,990 --> 00:30:53,470
Then, without saying a word, he crossed the kitchen, opened the cabinet beside my shoulder,

329
00:30:54,010 --> 00:30:59,090
and took out a glass. He filled the glass with water at the sink. He set the glass on the floor near my

330
00:30:59,090 --> 00:31:04,830
knee. He sat on the floor across from me. His back against the opposite cabinet, his legs stretched

331
00:31:04,830 --> 00:31:11,210
out in a way that made his feet almost touch mine, and he stayed. He didn't talk. He didn't ask.

332
00:31:11,670 --> 00:31:17,610
He didn't offer a shoulder. He stayed there. On the cold kitchen floor, with his rumpled shirt

333
00:31:17,610 --> 00:31:23,390
and his gaze on some point between my knee and the baseball, breathing slowly. I cried for two

334
00:31:23,390 --> 00:31:29,970
more minutes. I drank half the glass. I cried a little more. I drank the rest. When I stood up,

335
00:31:30,270 --> 00:31:35,290
he stood up too, without touching me. He collected the glass, carried it to the sink,

336
00:31:35,830 --> 00:31:41,470
washed it with the same calm he did everything else. Good night, Ayolanda. I went back to my room and

337
00:31:41,470 --> 00:31:47,530
took a long time to fall asleep again, but for another reason, the first public dinner came on Friday night.

338
00:31:47,610 --> 00:31:53,070
Il Jira Sole, a restaurant that served all of Providence without serving anyone properly,

339
00:31:53,670 --> 00:31:59,390
with a crystal chandelier and a metre, who lowered his head half a degree when Luda Vico entered.

340
00:31:59,850 --> 00:32:05,390
He told me at breakfast with a short sentence. In the way I already recognized as his way of asking

341
00:32:05,390 --> 00:32:11,130
without asking. Il Jira Sole, nine at night. It's important that we appear together.

342
00:32:11,690 --> 00:32:17,250
Dress? Whatever you think is good, I chose the dark blue one, the one with thin straps that

343
00:32:17,250 --> 00:32:21,270
held a mid-caf. I put on the only pair of earrings I'd brought from the old department.

344
00:32:21,790 --> 00:32:26,250
I came down the stairs with my hair pinned at the nape and saw Luda Vico waiting below,

345
00:32:26,630 --> 00:32:30,870
in a black suit that looked like it had been cut on his body, and an expression he managed to

346
00:32:30,870 --> 00:32:33,270
keep closed for three seconds before looking away.

347
00:32:34,330 --> 00:32:39,970
Let's go. He said. At the restaurant, everyone looked. No one stared.

348
00:32:40,470 --> 00:32:45,110
We sat at a table near the back. The metre poured the wine with slightly trembling hands.

349
00:32:45,110 --> 00:32:49,370
Luda Vico ordered for me without consulting me. A dish I wouldn't have ordered,

350
00:32:49,910 --> 00:32:55,010
and that was exactly the way I liked it. I raised an eyebrow. Does Donut Jira have a notebook of

351
00:32:55,010 --> 00:33:01,250
records? I asked. She has a memory. Her memory is about me, about everyone who sits at her table.

352
00:33:01,730 --> 00:33:07,130
I took a sip. Luda Vico. He looked up. Does this still feel more like a contract than a marriage?

353
00:33:07,610 --> 00:33:12,730
He held the glass by the stem, swirled the wine a quarter turn, set the glass back on the table

354
00:33:12,730 --> 00:33:19,290
without drinking. What would you rather it feel like? I don't know. I admitted. I'm still figuring it out.

355
00:33:19,670 --> 00:33:25,310
He almost smiled. Almost. It was at that moment that Renolfo Saravale crossed the restaurant.

356
00:33:25,730 --> 00:33:30,910
I didn't know who he was. I only felt the restaurant changed temperature before he reached the table.

357
00:33:31,410 --> 00:33:36,630
Luda Vico stiffened half a degree. Enough for me to notice. Not enough for anyone else to notice.

358
00:33:37,210 --> 00:33:41,190
Renolfo was a man in a light suit, a wide smile and heavy shoulders,

359
00:33:41,190 --> 00:33:46,170
with a colabrian accent that dragged the consonants in a strange way. Luda Vico,

360
00:33:46,850 --> 00:33:53,130
what a nice surprise. Renolfo. And this must be the new Mrs. Caracciolo. Renolfo turned to me

361
00:33:53,130 --> 00:33:59,610
with theatrical courtesy and extended his hand and immense pleasure. Before I could decide what to do with my hand,

362
00:33:59,950 --> 00:34:05,590
Luda Vico simply looked at him. He didn't speak. He didn't move. He just looked. The look

363
00:34:05,590 --> 00:34:10,990
lasted exactly the length of one breath and Renolfo understood. He withdrew his hand with the

364
00:34:10,990 --> 00:34:15,470
mile still hanging on his face, in the way of a man who knows he's lost this round,

365
00:34:15,910 --> 00:34:20,950
and that the next subject is better left untouched. Anyway, Renolfo said with forced

366
00:34:20,950 --> 00:34:27,130
lightness, good to see you Luda Vico. And good night, ma'am. He left. I kept looking at Luda Vico.

367
