another life. Maybe he was. The promise was you. He continued. His eyes fixed on mine. The

548
00:51:40,440 --> 00:51:45,700
deal between Adelmo and the Calabrian clan was simple. On the wedding day, the cerevaules would appear

549
00:51:45,700 --> 00:51:50,900
at the church. Adelmo would sign whatever he needed to sign and disappear through the back door.

550
00:51:51,400 --> 00:51:56,080
You'd leave with them. His debt would be forgiven. You'd be the payment in person.

551
00:51:56,600 --> 00:52:03,100
Something inside me went cold. In a way that left no tremor. Only silence. I clashed my hands in my

552
00:52:03,100 --> 00:52:09,700
lap so I wouldn't move. The wedding debt. He said, was built on top of that. The castanzo brothers

553
00:52:09,700 --> 00:52:14,660
have been a front for the cerevaules for three years. They collected your signature in the middle

554
00:52:14,660 --> 00:52:18,800
of the venue papers because they needed a rope around your neck in case the church plan failed.

555
00:52:19,320 --> 00:52:24,880
Two traps for the same day. One for you to walk in wearing white. Another so you'd have nowhere to

556
00:52:24,880 --> 00:52:30,560
run if the white dress wasn't enough. How did you find out? I said, and my voice came out steady,

557
00:52:31,120 --> 00:52:35,920
which  surprised  me.  Three  days  before  the  wedding.  My  lawyer  has  an  old  informant  in

558
00:52:35,920 --> 00:52:39,680
the

559
00:52:39,680 --> 00:52:45,300
house. The name crossed his desk by accident. Linked to Renolfo, Linked to yours. He brought it to

560
00:52:45,300 --> 00:52:51,420
me that same night. He stopped. Ranna's hand over his face. Then continued. I went after Adelmo

561
00:52:51,420 --> 00:52:56,920
that same early morning. I caught him at his place with a bag packed for another city that wasn't

562
00:52:56,920 --> 00:53:02,860
the one he told you. He confessed everything in 20 minutes. He cried. He begged forgiveness from the

563
00:53:02,860 --> 00:53:08,240
wall, not from you. I gave him two options. He disappears from Providence before dawn,

564
00:53:08,240 --> 00:53:13,780
with enough money to reach Newark and live quietly. Or I let the Sarah Falls find out he tried to escape

565
00:53:13,780 --> 00:53:19,900
the deal. He chose Newark before I finished the sentence. I closed my eyes. I saw Adelmo at the church

566
00:53:19,900 --> 00:53:26,360
in his suit, smiling for photos the week before. I saw the church bell tolling 12 times. I opened them

567
00:53:26,360 --> 00:53:31,880
again. You made him abandoned me at the altar. I made him abandon you before he sold you. The

568
00:53:31,880 --> 00:53:36,460
distinction landed between us like an open blade. It didn't hurt me the way it should have hurt.

569
00:53:36,460 --> 00:53:43,120
It just stayed there gleaming. The bell, I said. And the bell returned inside my head.

570
00:53:43,600 --> 00:53:48,720
Tolling slowly. You let the bell toll. I couldn't stop the bell without stopping the town.

571
00:53:49,140 --> 00:53:53,600
If I'd shown up at the church pulling you away by the arm, the Sarah Falls would know within

572
00:53:53,600 --> 00:53:59,620
two hours that I'd stepped in. You'd become a double target and I'd become a war. I let the bell

573
00:53:59,620 --> 00:54:06,060
toll because humiliation passes. The bullet doesn't. I swallowed hard. My mouth was dry in a strange

574
00:54:06,060 --> 00:54:13,000
way. The next day, he said, I bought the Costanzo's debt. I paid the $12,000 in your name

575
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:19,640
plus the rest the Sarah Falls expected to receive on the side. Two hours later, I had the paper in my hand.

576
00:54:20,460 --> 00:54:25,320
You no longer owed anyone anything. Except you didn't know that. And I couldn't come looking for

577
00:54:25,320 --> 00:54:29,680
you without the Sarah Falls understanding that their merchandise had a new owner. So you waited

578
00:54:29,680 --> 00:54:35,640
for me to lose my job. My apartment, my name. I waited for you to lose everything that still

579
00:54:35,640 --> 00:54:41,320
tied you to the town. He said, and his voice finally wavered because if I'd knocked on your door

580
00:54:41,320 --> 00:54:46,440
with money on Monday, you'd throw it in my face. If I'd knocked on your door on Wednesday,

581
00:54:47,080 --> 00:54:53,100
with you already having nowhere to go, you'd listen to me. I played you. I won't pretend I didn't.

582
00:54:53,560 --> 00:54:58,880
The silence pressed down. I heard my own pulse in my ear. The contract. I said,

583
00:54:59,160 --> 00:55:03,800
it was the only way I saw to have you under this roof without the Sarah Falls understanding what

584
00:55:03,800 --> 00:55:10,060
was. If you became my wife on paper, you became untouchable in Providence. No one touches the Don's

585
00:55:10,060 --> 00:55:15,760
wife without starting a war. No one wants to start. The whole coldness, the separate rooms,

586
00:55:16,120 --> 00:55:22,720
the rules, the no questions, was to give you space, not to control you. I didn't know how to offer

587
00:55:22,720 --> 00:55:28,620
you protection without it looking like a prison. I chose wrong. I chose too cold. I stayed quiet.

588
00:55:28,620 --> 00:55:34,700
He waited. He didn't try to fill it. And a Delmo? I said afterward. The photo in Newark.

589
00:55:35,260 --> 00:55:40,120
I pay a man to keep an eye on him. Not because I care about a Delmo. Because as long as he's alive

590
00:55:40,120 --> 00:55:45,240
in some corner, the Sarah Falls think the original deal can still be collected. The day he decides

591
00:55:45,240 --> 00:55:50,620
to come back to Providence thinking he can turn the tables. I need to know before he does. That's what

592
00:55:50,620 --> 00:55:57,860
that note meant. Silence paid. His silence. Not mine with you. I stood up. I didn't know where I was

593
00:55:58,340 --> 00:56:03,640
I only knew I couldn't stay sitting. I walked to the library window, leaned my forehead against

594
00:56:03,640 --> 00:56:08,760
the glass, and looked at the dark garden. His reflection appeared behind mine in the glass.

595
00:56:09,320 --> 00:56:17,220
Seated. Still waiting. I need air. I said, go. I left the library with a firm step and went down

596
00:56:17,220 --> 00:56:22,360
the corridor to the back of Miranda. The drizzle had stopped. The winter garden had its light low,

597
00:56:22,740 --> 00:56:27,580
and the veranda was empty. I leaned against the iron railing and breath deeply for the first time

598
00:56:27,580 --> 00:56:33,780
in an hour. And then I cried. I didn't cry over a Delmo. I cried over the weeks I'd slept in that

599
00:56:33,780 --> 00:56:39,240
room thinking I was merchandise. I cried over the church bell, tolding 12 times. Knowing now that

600
00:56:39,240 --> 00:56:44,260
behind that bell, there had been a plan to hand me over behind a cabinet. I cried over the glass

601
00:56:44,260 --> 00:56:49,400
of water he'd set beside my knee in the kitchen weeks ago, and that I'd seen at the time as

602
00:56:49,400 --> 00:56:55,120
elegant coldness. And now saw as the only thing he knew how to do without frightening me.

603
00:56:55,920 --> 00:57:00,520
I cried because I'd spent weeks thinking I was his shield when in fact he was the one who had

604
00:57:00,520 --> 00:57:07,320
become mine. He didn't come after me. I stayed there until the sky went fully dark. When I went back

605
00:57:07,320 --> 00:57:12,440
to the library, he was still sitting in the same armchair. The folder closed on the little table.

606
00:57:12,900 --> 00:57:19,340
His hands and his lap intertwined. You should have told me. I said from the doorway. I was going to tell

607
00:57:19,340 --> 00:57:25,100
you when you no longer needed me. He said, without raising his eyes, that sentence landed in

608
00:57:25,100 --> 00:57:32,040
strange way. I stood there absorbing it. That's pride, Lutavico. I said, low. That's fear with a

609
00:57:32,040 --> 00:57:39,100
pretty  name.  He  raised  his  eyes.  He  didn't  look  away.  It  is.  He  said,  I  know.  I

610
00:57:39,100 --> 00:57:40,440
sat  back  down  in  the  armchair

611
00:57:40,440 --> 00:57:45,960
across from him. I looked at him for a stretch of time. I didn't measure. He didn't rush me. Tomorrow,

612
00:57:46,680 --> 00:57:52,880
I said, finally, I want the three elders here. In this hall, I'm going to speak with them.

613
00:57:52,880 --> 00:57:59,340
I'llanda, I'm calling them. Not you. They called me a bot bride behind my back. I want them to hear

614
00:57:59,340 --> 00:58:05,620
me face to face. He was silent for a few seconds. Then he said, tomorrow night. Tomorrow night,

615
00:58:05,960 --> 00:58:10,860
I stood up and went up the stairs slowly. I didn't go to my room. I walked to the end of the left

616
00:58:10,860 --> 00:58:16,480
corridor. Stopped at the door I'd never opened and went back to my room because it wasn't yet time.

617
00:58:16,820 --> 00:58:21,580
But I knew it was a matter of hours. I slept little. I dreamed of the church bell

618
00:58:21,580 --> 00:58:27,320
holding 12 times and of his hand setting a glass of water beside my knee. The next night,

619
00:58:27,700 --> 00:58:33,620
the main hall was lit as if for a family dinner. And it wasn't. The three elders arrived 15 minutes

620
00:58:33,620 --> 00:58:38,800
apart from each other. Don Vittario came first. Tall and thin with a silk scarf inside his

621
00:58:38,800 --> 00:58:45,340
overcoat. Don Emiliano next. Stokki with the crest of the split crown lion on his pinky ring

622
00:58:45,340 --> 00:58:52,020
and an unlit cigarette between his fingers. Don Cisto last bent by the ears with a silver handled

623
00:58:52,020 --> 00:58:58,020
cane. The family lawyer, Fausto Renieri, the same one Lutavico had mentioned in the library,

624
00:58:58,760 --> 00:59:02,960
arrived alongside the hardest of the three and stood leaning against one of the columns,

625
00:59:03,520 --> 00:59:08,140
silent, bastion stayed at the door. Lutavico waited on the other side of the hall,

626
00:59:08,440 --> 00:59:13,620
without interfering. I came down the stairs and the dark blue dress Donutiara had laid on the bed

627
00:59:13,620 --> 00:59:18,620
for me without asking. I stopped in the middle of the hall. The three elders looked at me the way

628
00:59:18,620 --> 00:59:24,500
you look at an expensive piece of China, assessing whether it's cracked. Gentlemen, I said,

629
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:30,100
and my voice came out steady. The three of you, at some point in the last month, called me a

630
00:59:30,100 --> 00:59:35,460
bride bought in some corner of this house. I know this because this house is large but not large enough

631
00:59:35,460 --> 00:59:42,360
for a whisper not to climb the stairs. Girl, Don Cisto began, his voice rasping. This is not the

632
00:59:42,360 --> 00:59:48,820
place for, I raised my hand. Let me finish. I was bought, yes, you're right about that part,

633
00:59:49,200 --> 00:59:54,360
but you're getting wrong as about the merchandise. The merchandise wasn't me. It was my life,

634
00:59:54,640 --> 00:59:59,200
and whoever paid for it paid so that it wouldn't be taken from me by another clan. You know which

635
00:59:59,200 --> 01:00:04,940
clan. You know by whom. I saw Donut, Miliano exchange a look with Donvittorio. I continued.

636
01:00:05,540 --> 01:00:11,000
I didn't come here to ask you to like me. It's none of my concern. I came to say only one thing.

637
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:16,600
I chose to stay. Not because of the contract. The contract still has almost a year to go,

638
01:00:16,860 --> 01:00:23,060
and you know better than anyone that paper tears. I stay because I chose to. No clause, no exit door,

639
01:00:23,260 --> 01:00:28,840
no price. My gaze crossed Ludovico's from the other side of the hall. He understood I was speaking to

640
01:00:28,840 --> 01:00:34,180
him too. His hand closed slowly around his own wrist. In the place where he wore his father's watch.

641
01:00:34,680 --> 01:00:40,580
That's all. I said to the elders, good night. I turned and went up the stairs. I didn't look

642
01:00:40,580 --> 01:00:45,500
back to know whether he was coming. I knew he was. He caught up with me in the middle of the upper

643
01:00:45,500 --> 01:00:50,560
corridor. He didn't speak. I walked three more steps and stopped in front of the door at the end of

644
01:00:50,560 --> 01:00:57,760
the left corridor. His mind was three doors back on the right. He stopped behind me. So close I felt his

645
01:00:57,760 --> 01:01:03,540
breath in my hair. I turned slowly. His eyes were dark in a new way, and his hand rose until

646
01:01:03,540 --> 01:01:08,760
it almost touched my face and stopped in the air, waiting. I took his hand and pressed it to my

647
01:01:08,760 --> 01:01:12,820
face  myself.  He  let  out  his  breath  like  someone  who'd  been  holding  it  for  months.

648
01:01:18,330 --> 01:01:19,130
His  hand  was  warm

649
01:01:19,130 --> 01:01:26,330
on my cheek. Mine over his, trembled for half a second and stopped. If you come in here, he said,

650
01:01:26,530 --> 01:01:32,990
low, his eyes on mine. There's no more contract between us. Good. I said, he leaned his forehead

651
01:01:32,990 --> 01:01:38,010
against  mine.  We  stayed  there,  breathing  the  same  air  of  the  corridor.  The  sounds

652
01:01:38,010 --> 01:01:43,430
of  the  house

653
01:01:43,430 --> 01:01:48,670
seeming to know that this instant was ours alone. The corridor was dark except for the yellow

654
01:01:48,670 --> 01:01:53,250
light of the sconce at the end of the wall. And that light rested on his face in a way I wouldn't have

655
01:01:53,250 --> 01:02:00,230
had the courage to describe a loud. Then he kissed me. It was just one kiss. Slow, long, quiet,

656
01:02:00,790 --> 01:02:05,590
like someone finally saying a sentence he'd rehearsed for weeks, and discovered was simpler than

657
01:02:05,590 --> 01:02:11,350
he'd imagined. His hands slid down to my waist and stayed there with a firmness that wasn't urgency.

658
01:02:11,350 --> 01:02:16,930
It was decision. Mine rose to the nape of his neck, and the door at the end of the left corridor

659
01:02:16,930 --> 01:02:23,250
opened behind him. I went in. The door closed. I woke with sun on my face and didn't understand

660
01:02:23,250 --> 01:02:29,110
it first where I was. The window was different. Larger, facing the side garden I'd never seen

661
01:02:29,110 --> 01:02:35,210
from that angle. The curtains were heavy linen. The color of sand. Not the light white ones of my room.

662
01:02:35,630 --> 01:02:41,090
The smell of the air was different, too. Dark wood. Something citrusy and clean that I'd already

663
01:02:41,090 --> 01:02:45,950
learn to associate with him without realizing when I'd learned it. And there was a hand on my back,

664
01:02:46,370 --> 01:02:51,970
broad, warm, resting on my spine with the calm of someone who didn't intend to leave anytime soon.

665
01:02:52,370 --> 01:02:58,710
I turned slowly. Ludovica was awake, propped on his elbow. Looking at me the way a person looks when

666
01:02:58,710 --> 01:03:04,370
they finally allowed themselves to look, without controlling, without calculating. Just looking.

667
01:03:04,970 --> 01:03:10,450
As if I were a problem he'd given up solving and decided simply to have. Good morning. He said,

668
01:03:10,450 --> 01:03:16,590
his voice horse from morning. Deeper than usual. Good morning. He ran his thumb over the corner of my

669
01:03:16,590 --> 01:03:21,410
mouth. I don't know what he was checking, but he did it with the attention of someone verifying that

670
01:03:21,410 --> 01:03:26,750
something is still real. Half a laugh of mine escaped before I decided to let it. What is it?

671
01:03:27,010 --> 01:03:33,230
I'm trying to remember the name of my room. I said, I think I forgot. He laughed low. It was a sound

672
01:03:33,230 --> 01:03:39,330
I'd heard very few times. And that, that morning, seemed to open something in his chest. Something

673
01:03:39,330 --> 01:03:45,010
he'd kept closed for a long time. And now let out through that small crack. There was a knock at the door

674
01:03:45,010 --> 01:03:51,610
with two discrete taps. Dona Chiara's voice, from outside, crossed the wood with the same professional

675
01:03:51,610 --> 01:03:57,670
serenity as always. Coffee sir and madam. The tray is out here when you want it. I heard the sound of

676
01:03:57,670 --> 01:04:02,490
her footsteps moving away down the corridor, with a short pause at the end before she disappeared.

677
01:04:03,230 --> 01:04:08,490
Exactly the length of a contained smile. Calculated not to be heard, and completely audible

678
01:04:09,490 --> 01:04:14,330
Ludovico got up, put on his white shirt without buttoning it, went to the door and came back with the

679
01:04:14,330 --> 01:04:20,990
tray. Two fine porcelain cups, a saucer with thin biscuits, and my cup already set with two cubes

680
01:04:20,990 --> 01:04:26,130
in a drop of milk. I put both hands around it and said nothing. The warmth passed through the

681
01:04:26,130 --> 01:04:32,790
porcelain and warmed my palms. He saw that I saw. She knows that I know. He said, sitting again on

682
01:04:32,790 --> 01:04:38,110
the edge of the bed. I left it noted on the first day. I know you did. We drank the coffee

683
01:04:38,110 --> 01:04:43,830
without hurry. Through the window of his room, the side garden appeared whole. The hedges still

684
01:04:43,830 --> 01:04:49,270
with dew caught in the leaves. The morning light cutting through everything at a diagonal. It was a

685
01:04:49,270 --> 01:04:54,970
different view from the one in my room. More open. Deeper. I thought it would take me a while to get

686
01:04:54,970 --> 01:05:00,730
used to it. Then I realized I was getting used to it now. We went down together afterward. Bastion

687
01:05:00,730 --> 01:05:05,310
was crossing the hall with a folder under his arm, and the sure step of someone who has three

688
01:05:05,310 --> 01:05:10,370
tasks to solve before 10 in the morning. When he saw us come down side by side on the stairs,

689
01:05:10,850 --> 01:05:15,770
he stopped for a third of a second. The corner of his eye betrayed half a millimeter of curiosity,

690
01:05:16,430 --> 01:05:21,130
and he kept walking toward the library without breaking his step. I thought I was going to laugh.

691
01:05:21,570 --> 01:05:27,190
I held it. Dona Kiarra passed us in the kitchen corridor, carrying a basket of flowers cut from the

692
01:05:27,190 --> 01:05:32,290
garden. White hydranges and sprigs of rosemary and said, good morning, sir, and madam,

693
01:05:32,290 --> 01:05:37,450
with the same neutral intonation as always, except for the corner of her mouth that was making

694
01:05:37,450 --> 01:05:42,910
a visible and silent effort to stay still. Ludovico squeezed my hand inside his more firmly.

695
01:05:43,410 --> 01:05:48,470
His fingers interlacing mine, and made no comment. We continued down the corridor toward the

696
01:05:48,470 --> 01:05:52,750
garden as if coming down the stairs together on a Saturday morning where the most natural thing in

697
01:05:52,750 --> 01:05:59,230
the world. Maybe it already was. Outside, the day had dawned clear, with that firm winter blue

698
01:05:59,230 --> 01:06:04,130
that promises no warmth but delivers light to spare. The leaves still wet from the previous

699
01:06:04,130 --> 01:06:09,730
night's drizzle glistened. The air smelled of damp earth, and the thin smoke of coffee rising from

700
01:06:09,730 --> 01:06:16,230
the open kitchen. He led me to the stone bench beneath the Magnolia. Satt pulled me to sit beside him,

701
01:06:16,390 --> 01:06:23,030
and kept my hand inside his on his knee. No tie. No audience. No contract. Just the hand,

702
01:06:23,430 --> 01:06:28,430
and the cold bench beneath us, and the light hitting the Magnolia leaves that still had late blossoms

703
01:06:28,430 --> 01:06:34,210
high in the branches. It's the first time, I said low, that I hold you in public without it being

704
01:06:34,210 --> 01:06:41,250
for appearances. Yes, he didn't answer. He just squeezed gently. His thumb passing over my knuckles once.

705
01:06:41,670 --> 01:06:46,670
We stayed there a good while, without needing to fill it. A swallow landed on the edge of the stone

706
01:06:46,670 --> 01:06:52,230
fountain, drank, and flew away. The mansion's kitchen led out the smell of hot bread through the open

707
01:06:52,230 --> 01:06:56,990
window, something in my chest, which I'd been carrying clenched since the church bell,

708
01:06:56,990 --> 01:07:01,890
since the collector days of the door. Since the afternoon I signed a contract just to have

709
01:07:01,890 --> 01:07:08,330
somewhere to sleep, began to loosen slowly, not all at once. Slowly, like a knot that

710
01:07:08,330 --> 01:07:13,610
eased after being tied too tight for too long. Bastian came up the stone path with a firmer step

711
01:07:13,610 --> 01:07:19,930
than usual. He had an envelope in his hand. Ludovico raised his head, and I saw the exact moment he

712
01:07:19,930 --> 01:07:26,310
saw the envelope. His body changed. Not much, just in the shoulders, in the line of his jaw,

713
01:07:26,310 --> 01:07:32,110
in a way of straightening his spine that wasn't posture. It was alertness. It just arrived.

714
01:07:32,830 --> 01:07:39,290
Bastian said, handing the envelope into his hand. Man on a motorcycle didn't stop. Ludovico

715
01:07:39,290 --> 01:07:44,850
turned the envelope over. It was old. The darkened cream color of something that had spent time

716
01:07:44,850 --> 01:07:50,350
kept in a drawer or a safe. And on the back there was a red wax seal with the split crown

717
01:07:50,350 --> 01:07:56,710
lion crest stamped deep and with precision. The same crest is the Elder's Rings. The same as

718
01:07:56,710 --> 01:08:02,210
the Manchins main gate. Except that seal seemed older than the Rings. Older than the library's

719
01:08:02,210 --> 01:08:07,410
dark wood. Older than anything I'd touched in that house. He looked at the crest for two seconds

720
01:08:07,410 --> 01:08:12,670
longer than he should have. The garden was quiet. The swallow came back to the fountain and flew away

721
01:08:12,670 --> 01:08:18,050
again. Then he closed his hand around the envelope carefully. Thank you Bastian. Bastian

722
01:08:18,050 --> 01:08:23,330
nodded and went back up the stone path with nothing more. Ludovico stood up. I'll be right back.

723
01:08:23,750 --> 01:08:28,610
I followed him with my eyes down the covered corridor to the office. The door closed with a soft

724
01:08:28,610 --> 01:08:34,890
click. I sat on the bench. My hand marked by the warmth of his. Watching the swallow land for the

725
01:08:34,890 --> 01:08:40,130
third time on the edge of the fountain. I mentally counted the seconds without meaning to count. He

726
01:08:40,130 --> 01:08:46,450
came back at 42, without the envelope. With his hands in his pockets, his shoulders slightly lowered.

727
01:08:46,450 --> 01:08:52,050
His face composed back into the expression I'd learned to read beneath. He sat again beside me.

728
01:08:52,270 --> 01:08:57,790
He took my hand again. Firmer this time. Two firm for a Saturday morning that until a minute ago

729
01:08:57,790 --> 01:09:03,090
